2. Dataset 1 — ChestX-ray14 (NIH)
2.1 Description
ChestX-ray14 is a large-scale chest X-ray dataset released by the National Institutes of Health (NIH) Clinical Center. It is one of the most widely used public benchmarks in medical image analysis and serves as the imaging modality in this framework. The dataset contains frontal-view chest X-ray images collected from clinical routine examinations and is annotated with 14 common thoracic disease labels derived from radiology reports using natural language processing.
The dataset is particularly well-suited for training deep convolutional neural networks (CNNs) on radiological disease classification tasks. In our framework, a pretrained ResNet-50 or EfficientNet backbone processes these images to extract spatial hierarchical features representing structural abnormalities in the lung fields, mediastinum, and surrounding tissue.
2.2 Key Statistics
Total Images: 112,120 frontal-view chest X-ray images
Unique Patients: ~30,000 patients
Disease Categories: 14 thoracic conditions including Pneumonia, Effusion, Cardiomegaly, Atelectasis, Consolidation, and No Finding
Image Format: PNG, 1024 × 1024 pixels (resized to 224 × 224 for model input)
Label Type: Multi-label classification (a patient may have multiple conditions)
Positive Class Prevalence: 22.1% across splits
Dataset Split Used: 70% Train / 20% Test / 10% Validation — stratified at patient level
2.3 Preprocessing Applied
Images are normalized to match the pixel intensity distribution across different scanner types and acquisition settings. Random horizontal flips, rotations (±15°), and contrast adjustments are applied during training for data augmentation. All images are resized to 224 × 224 pixels to conform to CNN input requirements. At inference time, only center-crop resize and normalization are applied.
