3. Dataset 2 — MIMIC-III (PhysioNet)
3.1 Description
MIMIC-III (Medical Information Mart for Intensive Care III) is a large, freely available database comprising de-identified health data from over 38,500 patients admitted to the Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center (BIDMC) Intensive Care Units (ICUs) between 2001 and 2012. It is one of the most comprehensive and widely used clinical datasets in medical AI research.
MIMIC-III provides rich structured electronic health record (EHR) data including laboratory test results, vital sign measurements, clinical notes, ICD-9 diagnosis codes, medication records, and demographic information. In this framework, a selection of laboratory values and vital signs are extracted, preprocessed, and encoded through a Multilayer Perceptron (MLP) branch to capture structured clinical patterns associated with disease severity.
3.2 Key Statistics
Total Records: 58,976 ICU admissions
Unique Patients: ~38,500 patients
Data Types: Lab results, vital signs, ICD codes, demographics, medications, clinical notes
Key Features Used: Troponin, CRP, Creatinine, WBC, Heart Rate, SpO2, Blood Pressure, Age, Gender, Diagnosis codes
Positive Class Prevalence: 19.3% across splits
Dataset Split Used: 70% Train / 20% Test / 10% Validation — stratified at patient level
Missing Data Handling: Median imputation for continuous features; one-hot encoding for categorical
3.3 Preprocessing Applied
Continuous clinical variables such as laboratory values and vital signs are normalized using z-score standardization. Missing values are imputed using median imputation per feature. Categorical variables including diagnosis codes and gender are one-hot encoded. All features are aggregated per ICU admission to form a fixed-length structured feature vector of dimension 64.
