4. Dataset 3 — PhysioNet ECG Challenge 2020
4.1 Description
The PhysioNet/CinC Challenge 2020 dataset provides multi-lead electrocardiogram (ECG) recordings collected from multiple international clinical sites including hospitals in the USA, China, and Russia. The dataset was released as part of the PhysioNet/Computing in Cardiology Challenge 2020 with the goal of automating the detection of cardiac abnormalities from 12-lead ECG signals.
ECG time-series data serves as the sequential physiological modality in our framework. A Bidirectional Long Short-Term Memory (Bi-LSTM) network with temporal attention pooling processes fixed-length ECG windows to extract temporal features such as heart rate variability, rhythm abnormalities, and waveform morphology patterns. These temporal features are critical for identifying cardiovascular conditions early.
4.2 Key Statistics
Total Recordings: 10,000 ECG signal recordings
Unique Patients: ~6,000 patients
Signal Type: 12-lead ECG waveforms (.mat and .hea format)
Sampling Rate: 500 Hz (resampled to standard rate during preprocessing)
Window Length Used: 60-second fixed-length windows
Cardiac Conditions: 27 scored conditions including Atrial Fibrillation, Bundle Branch Block, ST-elevation, and Normal Sinus Rhythm
Positive Class Prevalence: 26.7% across splits
Dataset Split Used: 70% Train / 20% Test / 10% Validation — stratified at patient level
4.3 Preprocessing Applied
A Butterworth bandpass filter (0.5–40 Hz, order 4) is applied to remove baseline wander and high-frequency noise artifacts. Signals are then z-score normalized per recording. Fixed-length 60-second windows are extracted — random crop during training and center crop during evaluation. For recordings shorter than 60 seconds, zero-padding is applied.
